The thread is over so I'm going to give you the short version of the autistic story of the lore. What we now think of as SCP started as anonymous one-shot horror greentexts on /x/. Someone made a web page and compiled them, and people started to join the forums and stuff there, and came up with a semi-coherent setting and lore and recurring characters. This could have been amazing analog horror except for two things:

people writing this stuff, now that there was a coherent setting, turned it into a contest, a competition for the biggest, craziest, most implausible, most unstoppable world-ending threat that is slowly breaking loose and the SCP Foundation privately admits in its internal memos that there's sweet fuck-all they can do about it, and as a one-shot in isolation this mite B cool, but when there are thousands of entries, it raises the question of why the world still exists at all, and makes you wonder if something like https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aI0euMFAWF8 is happening

oh, and the forum and the wiki and everything else were taken over by people who really, really hate the creators, hate 4chan in general and /x/ in particular, hate the fandom, and think it's all "toxic" and "problematic," and use those words entirely. See image.

So an awful lot of the SCP stuff is overwrought but when you get down to it, pretty meh. To the extent that there was an overall theme to the original greentexts, it was sort of Lovecraftian "cosmic horror." There's all this weird shit out there, eating at the edges of reality, occasionally sticking their heads into our reality on their loooooooong six-dimensional necks and eating a few thousand people before the Foundation can intervene, drive them off, and brainwash and/or kill the witnesses to prevent a public panic that would make everything worse. It's impersonal horror from a universe that doesn't care about us. Too much of the material is amateurish personal gross-out horror.

Thus endeth the lore dump.
